{"type":"message","id":"5d87c046","parentId":"f9445cdd","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:13:59.367Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_onaw5ux4acrs_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 101236\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine the best action to take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- CFI analysis is complete (found in research/CFI_RESULTS.md)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n- Key insight: 5.7% of invariants have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n\r\nThe immediate next step according to the pending list is:\r\n- [ ] CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n\r\nI should start designing/implementing a CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would:\r\n1. Weight invariants by their CFI values\r\n2. Compare prediction quality vs frequency-only baseline\r\n3. Use the distinction between \"research trajectory\" (CFI>0.7) vs \"process artifacts\" (CFI=0)\r\n\r\nLet me check what's in the CFI_RESULTS.md to understand the data I have to work with, then create a compression experiment design.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at this more carefully - I need to take a concrete action that advances toward the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The most logical next step would be to:\r\n\r\n1. Create a compression experiment specification/design document\r\n2. Or modify the analysis to prepare for the experiment\r\n3. Or implement a simple CFI-weighted selection mechanism\r\n\r\nGiven the \"prefer file edits\" instruction, I should create or modify a file. Let me create a compression experiment design that outlines:\r\n- Hypothesis: CFI-weighted compression will preserve more research trajectory signal\r\n- Method: Compare CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression on next-pulse prediction\r\n- Success metrics: Prediction accuracy, trajectory coherence\r\n\r\nLet me write this as a new document in research/.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis identified that 5.7% of invariants have CFI>=0.7 (true causal anchors) while 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0). The natural next step is to test whether CFI-weighted compression outperforms frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression comparison, defining hypothesis, methodology, and success criteria.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only baseline by preserving research trajectory signals (CFI>=0.7) while filtering metaprogramming artifacts (CFI=0).\r\n\r\n## Method\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n- Sort invariants by frequency descending\r\n- Select top K tokens (K determined by compression ratio)\r\n- Baseline selection ignores temporal pattern entirely\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression\r\n- Weight each invariant: `score = frequency * CFI`\r\n- Sort by weighted score descending\r\n- Select top K tokens\r\n- This emphasizes invariants that are both frequent AND temporally consistent\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Data\r\n- Use invariants from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n- Each invariant: `{text, frequency, CFI}`\r\n- K values to test: 10, 25, 50, 100 tokens\r\n\r\n### Prediction Task\r\n- Given compressed invariant set, predict \"what will the next pulse focus on?\"\r\n- Measure: token overlap with actual next-pulse invariant set\r\n- Alternative: human evaluation of trajectory coherence\r\n\r\n### Success Metrics\r\n1. **Token Overlap Score**: % of actual next-pulse invariants correctly predicted\r\n2. **Research Trajectory Preservation**: % of CFI>=0.7 invariants retained in compression\r\n3. **Noise Rejection Rate**: % of CFI=0 invariants filtered from compression\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n| Metric | Frequency-Only | CFI-Weighted | Expected Delta |\r\n|--------|---------------|--------------|----------------|\r\n| Token Overlap | baseline | higher | +15-30% |\r\n| CFI>=0.7 Retention | ~30% | ~70% | +40% |\r\n| CFI=0 Rejection | ~50% | ~80% | +30% |\r\n\r\n## Implementation Notes\r\n- CFI=0 invariants represent metaprogramming artifacts (timestamps, formatting, session markers)\r\n- CFI>=0.7 invariants represent actual research progress (causal chain)\r\n- Weighting formula: `score = freq^α * CFI^β` (start with α=1, β=1)\r\n- Alternative: threshold first on CFI>=0.3, then sort by frequency\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n1. Extract invariant data into structured format (CSV/JSON)\r\n2. Implement compression selection algorithms\r\n3. Run retrospective test on past pulse invariants\r\n4. Compare prediction accuracy\r\n`\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:13:10\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774361639364}}
